{
  "doc_id": "36225",
  "text": "Patients with primary neurodegenerative speech and language disorders can present either with primary progressive aphasia (PPA) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] or progressive apraxia of speech (PAOS) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The term PPA is reserved for a neurodegenerative disorder in which the most salient feature is language dysfunction [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Three variants of PPA have been described which are each characterized by different patterns of language impairment [CITATION_7] . The agrammatic variant (agPPA) is characterized by written and verbal language that is grammatically flawed and sometimes with apraxia of speech (AOS); the semantic variant (svPPA) is characterized by anomia and loss of single-word knowledge; and the logopenic variant (lvPPA) is characterized by anomia without loss of word knowledge, difficulty with sentence repetition and phonologic errors. In contrast, the term PAOS describes a neurodegenerative disorder in which AOS is the presenting and most dominant clinical feature [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . These subjects can present with slow speech rate, articulatory distortions, distorted sound substitutions and segmentation of syllables in multisyllabic words or across words. Language impairment can be present, although it must be less severe than the AOS [CITATION_10] .",
